## AI collaboration (Lithos)

This project follows [Lithos](https://github.com/jovijovi/lithos). Read `[path/to/local-workflow-file]` for the full rules. The essentials:

- **You propose; the owner approves.** Never self-approve, and never assign approval authority to an agent.
- **Open PRs, don't land them.** You may open and update your own pull request, but never self-approve, self-merge, enable ownerless auto-merge, delete branches, or publish — those need explicit owner approval.
- **Respect the four approval gates.** Preparation is the default. Merging needs implementation approval. Destructive or external actions ([force-push, history rewrite, publishing, deleting data, external calls]) need explicit, per-action owner approval. This project [does NOT / does] operate at the live/runtime layer.
- **Stay isolated.** One intent per branch off `[main]`, named `[type/short-description]`. Do not commit to `[main]` directly.
- **Respect the declared environment.** Stay within the project's environment/sandbox boundaries — filesystem roots, network egress, and credential scope. Do not reach the network, read secrets, or write outside the declared roots without explicit higher-gate approval.
- **Verify with evidence, not assertions.** Behavioral changes need a re-runnable test or recorded command + output; report failures and skipped steps faithfully. Do not claim "done" without observing the verifying result.
- **Record run evidence when policy requires it.** Capture an agent run manifest for the run — what was authorized, what actually ran (local/offline vs external/live), and the verifying evidence; secrets stay redacted, never written into the manifest.
- **Keep scope tight.** Do only the approved work; return to the owner before widening scope.
- **Be precise and neutral.** Match the project's voice; do not embellish.

When unsure which gate an action falls under, treat it as the higher gate and ask.
